jek\n|\n|\n|\n|476\n|302\n|-\n|50\n|Pura\u0107i\n|\n|\n|\n|426\n|269\n|-\n|51\n|Ralutinac\n|\n|\n|\n|94\n|48\n|-\n|52\n|Ratkovac\n|\n|\n|\n|349\n|598\n|-\n|53\n|Skakavci\n|\n|\n|\n|365\n|227\n|-\n|54\n|Srpovci\n|\n|\n|\n|305\n|161\n|-\n|55\n|Hrva\u0107ani\n|\n|\n|\n|670\n|405\n|-\n|56\n|Crkvena\n|\n|\n|\n|721\n|468\n|-\n|57\n|\u010civ\u010dije\n|\n|\n|\n|374\n|228\n|-\n|58\n|\u010corle\n|\n|\n|\n|632\n|395\n|-\n|59\n|\u0160arinci\n|\n|\n|\n|862\n|510\n|-\n|60\n|\u0160ereg Ilova\n|\n|\n|\n|449\n|306\n|-\n|61\n|\u0160ibovska\n|\n|\n|\n|249\n|232\n|-\n|62\n|\u0160tivor\n|\n|\n|\n|402\n|119<br />\n|}\n\n===Ethnic composition===\nIn the end of the 19th century, during [[Austria-Hungary]], then sparsely populated area of the Municipality of Prnjavor was colonized by settlers from Eastern and Central Europe ([[Ukraine]], [[Italy|Italy (South Tirol)]], [[Hungary]], [[Poland]], [[Germany]], [[Austria]], [[Bohemia]], [[Slovakia]], etc.). At the time of the former [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia]] and due to numerous national minorities (about 20) Prnjavor was called \"Little Europe\". Except the [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]], [[Italians|Italian]] and [[Bohemians|Czech]] national minorities the others were mainly small communities. But, even today, besides the constitutive nations of [[Serbs]], [[Croats]], and [[Bosniaks]], a small number of [[Hungarians]], [[Slovaks]], [[Germans]], [[Polish people|Polish]], [[Slovenes]], [[Bulgarians]], [[Romanians]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]], [[Jews]], and [[Russians]] live in Prnjavor.\n\nAccording to the census of 1991 there were still 732 Italians in Bosnia and Herzegovina, thereof around 2/3 lived in municipality of Prnjavor, while at the end of the second world war most of the Italians had returned to Italy to today's [[Trento]] province. The Italians populated mainly the village of [[\u0160tivor]] in Prnjavor, where in 1991 73.13%<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mazzucchelli|first=Francesco|date=2017-06-25|title=Semiotiche dei confini e narrative spaziali della memoria in Bosnia Erzegovina: monumenti, musei, citt\u00e0|journal=Storicamente|volume=13|doi=10.12977/stor660|issn=1825-411X|doi-access=free}}</ref> of the population spoke Italian as their mother tongue.\n\nThe village school \"\u0160ibovska\" teaches in Italian language \"lingua d'insegnamento italiana\". It had in 1986 91 pupils and eight teachers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klemencic|first=Matjaz|last2=Zupancic|first2=Jernej|date=December 2004|title=The effects of the dissolution of Yugoslavia on the minority rights of Hungarian and Italian minorities in the post-Yugoslav states|journal=Nationalities Papers|volume=32|issue=4|pages=853\u2013896|doi=10.1080/0090599042000296186|issn=0090-5992}}</ref>\n\nThe Polish population that arrived during the Austro-Hungarian empire, mostly left after the second world war in the population exchanges where German population left from the Western Poland to Germany after redrawing of borders, and Polish population from different parts of Europe, including Prnjavor, returned to the empty areas in Western Poland, mainly [[Boles\u0142awiec|Boleslawiec]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reemigrancizbosni.pl|title=Stowarzyszenie Reemigrant\u00f3w z Bo\u015bni, ich Potomk\u00f3w oraz Przyjaci\u00f3\u0142 w Boles\u0142awcu {{!}} reemigranci z Jugos\u0142awii, przesiedlenia i migracje ludno\u015bci Polskiej, Polacy w Bo\u015bni, Polacy w Jugos\u0142awii, mieszka\u0144cy Boles\u0142awca|website=reemigrancizbosni.pl|language=pl-PL|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Ethnic composition \u2013 Prnjavor town\n|-\n|\n|[[\"Naselje Prnjavor\". nasbih.com. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|2013.]]\n|[[\"Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva Republike Bosne i Hercegovine 1991.\". fzs.ba. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1991.]]\n|[[Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva SFR Jugoslavije 1981.\". stat.gov.rs. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1981.]]\n|[[Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva SFR Jugoslavije 1981.\". stat.gov.rs. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1971.]]\n|-\n|[[\u010covjek|Total]]\n|8,484 (100,0%)\n|8,104 (100,0%)\n|6,187 (100,0%)\n|4,055 (100,0%)\n|-\n|[[Serbs]]\n|\u2013\n|3,891 (48,01%)\n|2,577 (41,65%)\n|1,545 (38,10%)\n|-\n|[[Bosniaks]]\n|\u2013\n|2,345 (28,94%)\n|1,915 (30,95%)\n|1,737 (42,84%)\n|-\n|[[Yugoslavs]]\n|\u2013\n|926 (11,43%)\n|907 (14,66%)\n|48 (1,184%)\n|-\n|Others\n|\u2013\n|723 (8,922%)\n|474 (7,661%)\n|423 (10,43%)\n|-\n|[[Croats]]\n|\u2013\n|219 (2,702%)\n|261 (4,219%)\n|275 (6,782%)\n|-\n|[[Montenegrins]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|25 (0,404%)\n|10 (0,247%)\n|-\n|[[Romani people|Roma]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|17 (0,275%)\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Slovenes]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|6 (0,097%)\n|10 (0,247%)\n|-\n|[[Albanians]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|5 (0,081%)\n|6 (0,148%)\n|-\n|[[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|1 (0,025%)\n|}\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Ethnic composition \u2013 Prnjavor municipality\n|-\n|\n|[[\"Op\u0107ina Prnjavor\". nasbih.com. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|2013.]]\n|[[\"Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva Republike Bosne i Hercegovine 1991.\". fzs.ba. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1991.]]\n|[[\"Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva SFR Jugoslavije 1981.\". stat.gov.rs. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1981.]]\n|[[\"Nacionalni sastav stanovni\u0161tva SFR Jugoslavije 1971.\". stat.gov.rs. Pristupljeno 22. 11. 2015.|1971.]]\n|-\n|Total\n|38,399 (100,0%)\n|47,055 (100,0%)\n|48,956 (100,0%)\n|46,734 (100,0%)\n|-\n|[[Serbs]]\n|30,673 (85,31%)\n|33,508 (71,21%)\n|34,699 (70,88%)\n|35,177 (75,27%)\n|-\n|[[Bosniaks]]\n|2,979 (8,285%)\n|7,143 (15,18%)\n|6,618 (13,52%)\n|6,143 (13,14%)\n|-\n|Others\n|1,853 (5,154%)\n|2,926 (6,218%)\n|3,045 (6,220%)\n|3,032 (6,488%)\n|-\n|[[Croats]]\n|451 (1,254%)\n|1,721 (3,657%)\n|2,060 (4,208%)\n|2,148 (4,596%)\n|-\n|[[Yugoslavs]]\n|\u2013\n|1,757 (3,734%)\n|2,400 (4,902%)\n|96 (0,205%)\n|-\n|[[Montenegrins]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|52 (0,106%)\n|38 (0,081%)\n|-\n|[[Romani people|Roma]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|42 (0,086%)\n|53 (0,113%)\n|-\n|[[Slovenes]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|31 (0,063%)\n|31 (0,066%)\n|-\n|[[Albanians]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|7 (0,014%)\n|10 (0,021%)\n|-\n|[[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]]\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|2 (0,004%)\n|6 (0,013%)\n|}\n<br />\n\n==Economy==\n[[Image:Ukrina.jpg|thumb|Old mill on [[Ukrina]]]]\n[[Image:Ribnjak fish.jpg|thumb|Fishing Ground Ribnjak]]\n\nThe municipality of Prnjavor has the following land resources: farmlands ({{Convert|437.79|km2|sqmi|0|abbr=on}}/68.8%), cultivable land ({{Convert|382.64|km2|sqmi|2|abbr=on}}), forest resources ({{Convert|173.39|km2|sqmi|2|abbr=on}}) and water resources (Ukrina River, Drenova Lake).\n\nConsidering that almost four-fifths of the population live in rural areas and reckoning with great areas of cultivable land, with all reason agriculture has been recognized as the key branch of the economy considering the Municipality development. In the area of Prnjavor more than {{Convert|200|km2|acre|-3|abbr=on}} of land are cultivated while {{Convert|6.1|km2|acre|-1|abbr=on}} is planted with fruit crops.\n\nOut of the total area of the cultivated farmlands, the cereal crops share is 77%, vegetable crops 10% while the rest has been sown with industrial crops, berries and fruit crops. New greenhouses are being constructed, health food production ([[organic agriculture]]) projects have been started to which the Municipality of Prnjavor has great predispositions due to the lack of significant industrial capacities as well as the preserved nature.\n\n;Economic preview\nThe following table gives a preview of total number of registered employed people per their core activity (as of 2016):<ref name=\"stats17\">{{cite web|title=Cities and Municipalities of Republika Srpska 2017|url=http://www2.rzs.rs.ba/static/uploads/bilteni/gradovi_i_opstine_republike_srpske/2017/Gradovi_Opstine_Republike_Srpske_2017_WEB.pdf|website=rzs.rs.ba|accessdate=20 October 2018|date=December 2017|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- \n! Activity\n! Total\n|- \n|Agriculture, forestry and fishing||align=\"right\"|128\n|- \n|Mining and quarrying||align=\"right\"|14\n|- \n|Manufacturing||align=\"right\"|1,976\n|- \n|Distribution of power, gas, steam and air-conditioning||align=\"right\"|91\n|- \n|Distribution of water and water waste management||align=\"right\"|130\n|- \n|Construction||align=\"right\"|105\n|- \n|Wholesale and retail, repair||align=\"right\"|1,330\n|- \n|Transportation and storage||align=\"right\"|266\n|- \n|Hotels and restaurants||align=\"right\"|317\n|- \n|Information and communication||align=\"right\"|65\n|- \n|Finance and insurance||align=\"right\"|64\n|- \n|Real estate activities||align=\"right\"|19\n|-\n|Professional, scientific and technical activities||align=\"right\"|167\n|- \n|Administrative and support services||align=\"right\"|31\n|- \n|Public administration and defence||align=\"right\"|314\n|- \n|Education||align=\"right\"|688\n|- \n|Healthcare and social work ||align=\"right\"|253\n|- \n|Art, entertainment and recreation||align=\"right\"|16\n|- \n|Other service activities||align=\"right\"|106\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|'''Total'''||align=\"right\"|'''6,070'''\n|}\n\n==Tourism and leisure==\n\n=== Nature ===\n'''Ribers and streams''', the great areas of timber-lands as well as the [[Ukrina|Ukrina's]] banks covered with greenery and the old mills make this river specially attractive for all the nature and fishing lovers. The Drenova lake and fishing ground Ribnjak both have a very good foundation for hunting and fishing development. In 2003 a record catch (a 91&nbsp;kg heavy catfish) was registered at this lake, otherwise being a fishing ground. \n\n'''Hunting grounds''', the hunting grounds on Mt. Motajica, in the forest lands of \u010cavka and Mt. Ljubi\u0107 as well as the fishing ground of Ribnjak have again become destinations for hunters from Germany, Austria and especially Italy.\n\n'''SRC \"Borik\"''', Borik  is a sports recreation center located north of the town Prnjavor, which consists of a forest park along which there are various camping spots, a very well known and popular restaurant among the locals \"Lova\u010dki dom\", as well as a volleyball court, outdoor gym and a children's playground.\n\n=== Recreation ===\n[http://banjakulasi.com '''Kula\u0161i Spa'''], {{Convert|14|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from the town of Prnjavor, has been known as a sanatorium ever since Austria-Hungarian rule in this area. Therapeutic factors: water is hyperalkalescent (pH 12.75) and includes [[hydrogen sulphide]] (H<sub>2</sub>S, HS<sup>+</sup>). The water is hyperthermal and its temperature is 28&nbsp;\u00b0C (82&nbsp;\u00b0F). Basic water characteristics: curative, oligomineral, thermomineral, hyperalkalic, chloride and sulphide water with the presence of calcium and sodium. Indications: degenerative skin disease (psoriasis, eczema, hair root sebreae, acne etc.) postoperative conditions, inflammatory diseases of the bone-joint-and-muscle system, liver, stomach, kidney and urinary tract diseases etc.\n\n'''[[Lipizzan]]er studs \"Vu\u010dijak\"''', founded in 1946, belongs to the group of the most famous horse farms from the time of ex-Yugoslavia. There are about fifty Lipizzaner head on it with significant presence of several breeding lines and stocks. It is located in the village of Lu\u017eanit. It currently offers horse riding classes and is going through a reconstruction to be able to offer services in the field of education, tourism and leisure as well as recreational and medical activities.\n\n=== Culture ===\n'''Stuplje and Liplje monasteries''', two twins and in books they are always mentioned together as the victims of burning during Ottoman reign. After having been burnt by the Ottomans during [[Austrian-Ottoman Wars|Austrian-Ottoman]] war they were neglected. The foundations of Stuplje were found in Gornji Vija\u010dani (village not far from Prnjavor) only in mid-1994. The reconstruction and building of this medieval monastery has been going on ever since.\n\n'''The Roman Catholic church of Saint Anthony of Padua''', located in the town of Prnjavor was built in 1909 during the Austro-Hungarian empire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biskupija-banjaluka.org/?page_id=1686|title=\u017dupa PRNJAVOR \u2013 BANJOLU\u010cKA BISKUPIJA|website=www.biskupija-banjaluka.org|language=hr|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\n'''The [[:bs:Gradska d\u017eamija u Prnjavoru|city]] mosque of Prnjavor''', located in the town of Prnjavor has been entered into the list of national heritage sites of Bosnia and Herzegovina, while it was destroyed during the war in 1992 but later rebuilt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://old.kons.gov.ba/main.php?id_struct=6&lang=1&action=view&id=834|title=Komisija za o\u010duvanje nacionalnih spomenika|website=old.kons.gov.ba|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\n'''The log-built church in Pala\u010dkovci''', located in the village of Gornji Pala\u0107kovci is one of the most important cultural monuments in the municipality. It is devoted to apostles St Peter and St Paul and was built in 1843 in the period of Ottoman rule. In terms of its construction and engineering as well as aesthetically it is a real small master-piece of popular architecture. Even at the time of Yugoslavia it was declared a worldwide cultural heritage monument and was put under the protection of the state. It is currently, among other monuments, on the list under consideration to be mentioned as a cultural heritage of Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kons.gov.ba/Default.aspx?langTag=bs-BA&template_id=175&pageIndex=1|title=Komisija za o\u010duvanje nacionalnih spomenika|website=kons.gov.ba|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kons.gov.ba/nacionalni_spomenici/privremena_lista/Default.aspx?id=7281&langTag=bs-BA|title=PRIVREMENA LISTA NACIONALNIH SPOMENIKA|website=kons.gov.ba|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n\nPrnjavor's local football club is [[FK Ljubi\u0107 Prnjavor|FK \"Ljubi\u0107\" Prnjavor]], which plays in the [[First League of the Republika Srpska]].\n\nThe club was founded in 1946 and until 1991 it had little importance in the football world of the SFRY. With the disintegration of Yugoslavia, this club finally managed to reach the public. It started in 1992 in the Second League of Republika Srpska, then in 1993 it moved to the First League of Republika Srpska. It left the First League in 1996, but returned the following season. It is currently in the Second League of Republika Srpska. It plays at the City Stadium \"Borik\" in Prnjavor which has a capacity of about 2500 people.\n\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\nPrnjavor is [[town twinning|twinned]] with the following cities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://opstinaprnjavor.net/little-europe/sister-cities/?lang=en|title=SISTER CITIES {{!}} Op\u0161tina Prnjavor|website=opstinaprnjavor.net|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Boleslawiec]], Poland\n* {{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[Zhydachiv]], Ukraine\n* {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Boskovice]], Czech Republic\n\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Milan Bjegojevi\u0107]], former basketball player and coach\n*[http://balkans.aljazeera.net/tag/tarik-dodic Tarik \u0110o\u0111i\u0107], author and CEO of [[Al Jazeera Balkans]]\n*[https://www.slu.se/en/cv/faruk-djodjic/ Faruk \u0110o\u0111i\u0107], researcher\n* \n* \n* \n* \n* \n* [[Neven Suboti\u0107]], football player\n* [[Milan Marinkovi\u0107]], former basketball player and coach\n* [[Marko Todorovi\u0107 (actor)|Marko Todorovi\u0107]], actor\n* [[Cvjetko Popovi\u0107]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Municipalities of Republika Srpska]]\n*[[Schutzberg, Bosnia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Prnjavor}}\n*[http://www.opstinaprnjavor.net/ Official website]\n*[https://prnjavorski.net/ Prnjavorski informativni portal]\